  "doc_id": "31912",
  "text": "In both desktop and embedded systems, SRAM and DRAM are the two most common writable memory organizations used for program data allocation. SRAM is fast but expensive while DRAM is slower (by a factor of 10 to 100) but less expensive (by a factor of 20 or more). To combine their advantages, a large amount of DRAM is often used to provide low-cost capacity, along with a small-size SRAM to reduce runtime by storing frequently used data. The proper use of SRAM in embedded systems can introduces an average of 2x speedup compared to using DRAM only. This gain is likely to increase in the future since the speed of SRAM is increasing by 60% a year versus only 7% a year for DRAM [CITATION_1] .",
